The paper deals with distributed protocols for consensus in a network, which is a topic that falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The use of randomized protocols and the focus on efficiency suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the relationship between consensus and load balancing, which is a topic that falls under the sub-category of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI). The use of probability and the analysis of the efficiency of the protocols suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-category of Information Theory (cs.IT). Finally, the paper proposes a framework for designing protocols that generalize to different problem parameters, which is a topic that falls under the sub-category of Machine Learning (cs.LG).
